Excercise 2 - linear regression model

Introduction and data

We are analyzing data from a survey of students enrolling in the course (Introduction to Social Statistics, fall 2014 - in Finnish).

The data is imported from this repository with the code below, and the structure and dimensions of data is checked.

learning2014 <- read.table("data/learning2014.txt")
str(learning2014)
## 'data.frame':    166 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ gender  : Factor w/ 2 levels "F","M": 1 2 1 2 2 1 2 1 2 1 ...
##  $ age     : int  53 55 49 53 49 38 50 37 37 42 ...
##  $ attitude: num  3.7 3.1 2.5 3.5 3.7 3.8 3.5 2.9 3.8 2.1 ...
##  $ deep    : num  3.58 2.92 3.5 3.5 3.67 ...
##  $ stra    : num  3.38 2.75 3.62 3.12 3.62 ...
##  $ surf    : num  2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83 ...
##  $ points  : int  25 12 24 10 22 21 21 31 24 26 ...

We imported the data from a .txt file and can see that there are 166 observations (students) and 7 variables. Variables include gender, age, Global attitude towards statistics, and combined variables that are the mean of questions in the dimensions of deep, strategic and surface, and finally points on the exam.

Let´s explore the data!

# i increased the figure size for readability in the r code chunk header. See source code for details
# access the GGally and ggplot2 libraries
library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)

# create a plot matrix with ggpairs()
p <- ggpairs(learning2014, mapping = aes(col = gender, alpha = 0.3), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))
# draw the plot
p

This shows a scatter matrix of the observations grouped by gender. There were more females in the course. Correlations between variables can be seen as black after “Cor:” The highest correlation can be found between attitude and points.

Regression analysis

We´ll create linear regression models for attitude, deep and stra as explanatory variables with points as target variable, and print out a summary

#we assign the linear model to themodel
themodel <- lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra + deep, data = learning2014)
summary(themodel)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra + deep, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.5239  -3.4276   0.5474   3.8220  11.5112 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.3915     3.4077   3.343  0.00103 ** 
## attitude      3.5254     0.5683   6.203 4.44e-09 ***
## stra          0.9621     0.5367   1.793  0.07489 .  
## deep         -0.7492     0.7507  -0.998  0.31974    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.289 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2097, Adjusted R-squared:  0.195 
## F-statistic: 14.33 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 2.521e-08

In this linear model Exam points are positively correlated with attitude towards statistics by a factor of 3.53. p is very small, 4.12e-09 which tells us that the null hypothesis (i.e. that attitude has no effect on points) is false. We can conlude that a positive attitude towards statistics in general is a predictor of higher exam points!

With regards to the predictors deep and stra p is above the commonly used limit of 0.05 and thus they are not statistically significant predictors of exam points.

We´ll remove deep and stra from the model and run it again.

modelatt <- lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
summary(modelatt)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

According to the model, for each 1 point increase in attitude, the exam points are incresed by 3.53 points. The relationship is statistically significant: p = 4.119e-09.

R squared is a measure of how much of the total variation is explained by the model. Multiple R squared is 0.1906, indicating that in this model attitude accounts for 19% of variance in exam points.

Validation of the model

Finally we´ll produce diagnostic plots for the model.

# We use the function plot.lm, see ?plot.lm for help. Several diagnostic plots could be drawn at once using plot(modelatt, which = c(1,2,5,))
plot(modelatt, which = c(1))

The residuals vs fitted plot tells us about the distribution of residuals with regards to fitted values. The assumption is that the distribution of residuals should be normal, and should not depend on the explanatory values. There is a slight tapering of residuals towards the higher end of expected values, suggesting that there is a small subpopulation of those with higher attitude scores having less variance than the rest of the population. There are also a couple of outliers with higher negative variance. Otherwise the residuals seem evenly distributed.

plot(modelatt, which = c(2))

The q-q plot is a way to inspect the distribution of our data. Normally distributed data should fall on a straight line. Our plot is only slightly curved towards the ends and most observations fall on the line.

plot(modelatt, which = c(5))

In the residuals vs. leverage plot we are looking for observations that fall in the upper or lower right corners. No such observations can be found, and thus we have no outliers that are harmful to the model

I conclude that the linear regression model with attitude as an explanatory variable and exam points as dependent is valid.

Excercise 3 - Logistic regression

Introduction and data

We are exploring data from two questionnaires focusing on high school student performance and alcohol consumption from two portuguese schools.

We import the data into R from a local data file. Source data can be found here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance

alc <- read.table("data/alc.txt")
colnames(alc)

There are variables in the data are listed above. There is binary, nominal and numeric data relating to background and behavior of students. G1-G3 are grades, (g3 is the final grade). “alc_use” is constructed as the mean of “Dalc” and “Walc”, “high_use” is a binary TRUE or FALSE for high alcohol use (TRUE when alc_use >2). More detailed information can be found behind the link above.

We are going to study the relationships between high/low alcohol consumption and these 4 arbitrarily choosen variables:

  • Medu - Mothers level of education (numeric 0-4). 0 is none, 4 is higher education. Hypothesis: Lower alcohol consumption with higher mothers education level.
  • abscences - number of school abscences (numeric 0 to 45) Hypothesis: many abscences related to higher alcohol consumption.
  • schoolsup - extra educational support (binary yes or no) Hypothesis: need of school support related to higher alcohol consumption.
  • failures - number of previous class failure (numeric: range 0-3): Hypothesis: previous failures relates to hihger alcohol consumption.
# initialize a plot of high_use and Medu

Logistic regression

We use the function glm() to fit a logistic regression model “m” with high_use as target, and Medu, abscences, schoolsup and failures as predictors and print a summary.

m <- glm(high_use ~ Medu + absences + schoolsup + failures, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ Medu + absences + schoolsup + failures, 
##     family = "binomial", data = alc)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -2.2871  -0.8081  -0.7056   1.2096   1.9285  
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  -1.49792    0.36611  -4.092 4.29e-05 ***
## Medu          0.05863    0.11326   0.518 0.604693    
## absences      0.08581    0.02305   3.723 0.000197 ***
## schoolsupyes -0.42697    0.36812  -1.160 0.246102    
## failures      0.53531    0.19401   2.759 0.005794 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 465.68  on 381  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 438.37  on 377  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 448.37
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

Abscences and failures are statistically positively associated with high use of alcohol. (p <0.05)

Next we compute odds ratios with confidence intervals from the coefficients of the model with the exp function.

# compute odds ratios
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp

# compute confidence intervals (CI)
CI <- confint(m) %>% exp
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
# print out the odds ratios with their confidence intervals
cbind(OR, CI)
##                     OR     2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept)  0.2235938 0.1067127 0.4499919
## Medu         1.0603825 0.8505919 1.3273428
## absences     1.0896003 1.0437001 1.1424496
## schoolsupyes 0.6524844 0.3050016 1.3052315
## failures     1.7079772 1.1703297 2.5182154

The confidence intervals for Medu and schoolsup include the number 1 in the 95% confidence interval range, and thus the association with these and alcohol use is not statistically significant, just as we found in the summary of our model previously. OR 1.089 for abscences means that for each additional abscence the odds for high use of alcohol is 8.9% higher. The same goes for class failures, but the odds are even higher OR = 1.708.

Predictions of the model vs. actual values

Well rebuild the model using the statistically significant predictors failures and abscences, calculate probabilities for each individual and compare them to actual values.

# fit the model
m2 <- glm(high_use ~ failures + absences, data = alc, family = "binomial")

#  predict() the probability of high_use and add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = predict(m2, type = "response"))

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use( true if prob >0.5)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   258   10
##    TRUE     99   15

This gives us 10 false positives, and 99 false negatives out of 382 observations. That gives a probability of 0.2853403 for false classification. Guessing woud give a probability of 0.5, so this model preforms about twice as good as pure guesswork.

With ´scale()` on default settings we center the data on 0, and divide each variable by its standard deviation, effectively making the SD = 1 for each variable. We do this due to the requirements of Linear discriminant analysis.

Some data wrangling

Now we create a categorical variable for crime rate from the quantiles of crim. Also we divide the data into a train and test set with 80% of data in the train set. Well remove the correct crime classes from the test set after saving them separately as true_crime.

# create a quantile vector of crim 
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

# create a categorical variable 'crime' with the quantiles.
lblz <- c("low", "med_low", "med_high","high")
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, labels = lblz, include.lowest = TRUE)

# remove original crim from the dataset
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

# add the new categorical value to scaled data
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

# randomly choose 80% of rows, yields 404 rows.
selection <- sample(nrow(boston_scaled), size = 0.8*nrow(boston_scaled))

#gen train set
train <- boston_scaled[selection,]

#gen test set
test <- boston_scaled[-selection,]

# remove correct classes from test set.
true_crime <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

After this data wrangling we are ready for linear discriminant analysis with crime as target variable, and all others as predictors.

#we fit the modelwith crime
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

# we define a function for producing arrows in the plot
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "magenta", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

#
crime_classes <- as.numeric(train$crime) #for colors in plot
plot(lda.fit, col = crime_classes, pch = crime_classes, dimen =2)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale =2)

#plot(boston_scaled$crime, boston_scaled$rad)

Our first linear discriminant LD1, which is on the x-axis separates the high from low to med_high classes very well, whereas LD2 (y axis) does not do a too good job on this, slthoug separation between low and med_high is apparent. I guess that our model would be good at predicting wether crime rate is exceptionally high. The predictor with most influence is rad (accessibillity to radial highways), followedby zn and nox.

We´ll predict classes in the test dataset.

# did the removing of crime from test set already in the chunk "categorize crime"
# predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

# cross tabulate the results
table(correct = true_crime, predicted = lda.pred$class)

##   low       18      11        0    0
##   med_low    8      15        4    0

##   high       0       0        0   22

The model is able to predict crime rate class pretty well. It has most trouble separating med_low from its neighbors.

Excercise 5 - Dimensionality reduction techniques

Introduction and data

We are using the human dataset, which originates from the United Nations Development Programme. This dataset has 8 variables and 155 observations, all of which are different countries. The variables and descriptions are shown below.

Variable Explanation
mat.mort Maternal mortality
ado.BR Adolescent birth rate
parl.rep Female share of parliamentary seats
eduratio Ratio of F to M with secondary education
laboratio Ratio of F to M in labour force
life.exp Life expectancy at birth
edu.exp Excpected years of schooling
GNI.pc Gross national income per capita 
ggpairs(human)

Distribution of most variables look skewed, except for edu.exp which seems normally distributed. There are also a bunch of apparent correlations between variables, eg. edu.exp and life.exp

corrplot(cor(human), method="circle", type="lower", cl.pos="b", tl.pos="d", tl.cex=0.7)

The correlations are better visualized here. For example: Strong correlation between Maternal mortality and Adolescent birth rate.

humansummary <- summary(human)

PCA doesn´t work properly on unscaled data. The mean GNI per capita is > 1000 times the mean of the next highest (Maternal mortality) and thus it´s the only variable that shows in the plot. Data should be scaled for PCA. The error messages above relate to arrows in the plot which would be of zero length because of scaling issues.

#scale with default options (center to 0 and divide by SD)
human2 <- scale(human)
#perform PCA on scaled human data
pca_human2 <- prcomp(human2)

# draw a biplot of the principal component representation and the original variables
biplot(pca_human2, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.7, 1.0), col = c("grey20", "red"))

This looks better. Principal component 1 is affected by 6 out of 8 variables in the data to a similar degree. Adolescent birth rate and maternal mortality are positively correlated, but negatively correlated with the following group of phenomenons, (which again are positively correlated): life expectancy, education expectancy, ratio of females to males receiving secondary education, and GNI per capita. Uncorrelated with the previous, but correlated with eachother are percentage of females in parliament, and ratio of females to males in the labour force. These two affect the secondary principal component.

So i conclude that GNI, and availability of education - for both genders are positively correlated with life expectancy, and adolescent births and maternal mortality are inversely correlated with these. Percentage of females in the work force and as representatives in parliament are not correlated with the phenomenons above.

Excercise 6 - Longitudinal data.

MABS chapter 8 analyses on RATS data

In the RATSL data we have 16 individual rats in 3 feeding Groups with different diets. The rats are followed for ~8 weeks (Timein days). The Weight of the rats is measured. There are 176 weight measurements in total.

We´ll plot the individual weight curves:

ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = Time, y = Weight, colour = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(RATSL$Weight), max(RATSL$Weight)), name="Weight (grams)")

There are some clearly visible differences in starting weights between groups. Group 1 rats weigh less than group 2 and 3. All weights tend to increase with time. The slope in group 1 is not as steep as in groups 2 or 3.

We´ll standardize the data and do the same plot again.

RATSL <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  mutate(stdWeight = (Weight - mean(Weight))/sd(Weight)) %>%
 # mutate(sclWeight = scale(Weight)) %>% #scale does the same thing as we learned earlier.
  ungroup()
  
ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = Time, y = stdWeight, colour = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(RATSL$stdWeight), max(RATSL$stdWeight)), name="Weight, standardized")

In plot on standardized values we see that most lines are approximately horizontal, and this goes for all groups. Fat rats stay fat and slim rats stay slim, relatively speaking, althoug the absolute weight values increased as we saw in the first plot. This is called the `tracking phenomenon.

We now plot mean weights of groups + SEM

# Number of measurement points, baseline included
n <- RATSL$Time %>% unique() %>% length()

Relative weights

# I want to look at relative weight increase when compared to starting weights, and calculate it with the following command:

RATSL <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(ID,Group) %>%
  mutate(Weight_rel = Weight/Weight[Time == 1]*100)

# Number of measurement points, baseline included
n <- RATSL$Time %>% unique() %>% length()

# Summary data with mean and standard error of bprs by treatment and week 
RATSSummary_rel <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Group, Time) %>%
  summarise( mean = mean(Weight_rel), se = (sd(Weight_rel)/sqrt(n))) %>%
  ungroup()

# Plot the mean profiles
ggplot(RATSSummary_rel, aes(x = Time, y = mean, color = Group, shape = Group)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("red","green","blue")) +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(1,2,3)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-se, ymax=mean+se, linetype=NULL), width=0.3) +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.8,0.4)) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(Weight) +/- se(Weight)")

The relative weight gains are quite similar, but group 2 seems to gain weight a little faster. Lets boxplot this after removing baseline measurements

RATSLBs <- RATSL %>%
  filter(Time > 1) %>%
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  summarise(mean=mean(Weight_rel)) %>%
  ungroup()

# Draw a boxplot of the mean versus Group
ggplot(RATSLBs, aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(relative weight in %, without baseline measurement", breaks=seq(100,110,1))

I´m happy with the plot, the difference seems to persist between G2 and G3. Let´s test.

# Add the baseline (100) to the summary data
RATSLBs <- RATSLBs %>%
  mutate(baseline = 100)

# Fit the linear model with the mean as the response 
fit <- lm(mean ~ baseline + Group, data = RATSLBs)

# Compute the analysis of variance table for the fitted model with anova()

anova(fit)

The anova gives us p =0.29. This tells us that no significant differences in relative weight gains exist between groups.

MABS chapter 9 analyses on BPRS data.

We read the BPRS data in long form, factorize subjectand treatment variables. and have a look at the data. Later i realized there is a danger in the data: Subjects are numbered 1-20 in each treatment group, but in the MABS book it was clearly stated that there were 40 men in the data. Therefore we paste ´subject´ and ´treatment´ to create a new factor variable, subject 2 which we use to separate the 40 individuals. This has significance in creating the random effects models.

BPRSL <- read.table("data/BPRSL.txt")

BPRSL$subject <- factor(BPRSL$subject)
BPRSL$treatment <- factor(BPRSL$treatment)
BPRSL <- mutate(BPRSL, subject2=factor(paste(BPRSL$subject, BPRSL$treatment)))

The data consists of values of Brief Psychiatric Rating Scale (BPRS) in 40 men in 2 treatment groups followed up for 8 weeks and baseline (week 0) A plot of the data is seen below. For the plot we group data by ìnteraction(subject,treatment)

ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = bprs, group = subject2)) +
  geom_line(aes(colour = treatment)) + scale_x_continuous(name = "Time (weeks)", breaks = seq(0, 8, 1)) +

No clear distinction between groups or any trend can be identified from this plot.

We´ll ignore that the data consists of repeated measures, and fit a multiple linear regression model with bprs as response, and week and treatment as explanatory variables.

bprs_lrm <- lm(bprs ~ week + treatment, BPRSL)

Ignoring the longitudinal nature of the data the linear regression model indicates that treatment has no effect, whereas with increasing weeks bprs scores decrease by approximately 2.27/week.

Random intercept

We´ll now fit a random intercept model using the package ´lme4´ with week and treatment as explanatory variables, and subject as random effect to account for differences in individuals intercept ~ starting values of bprs scores.

# Create a random intercept model
BPRS_rim <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (1 | subject2), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)

# Print the summary of the model
summary(BPRS_rim)

Random intercept and random slope

Then we fit a random intercept and random slope model to also account for individuals random slopes in bprs scores vs. time.

# create a random intercept and random slope model
BPRS_rism <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (week | subject2), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)

# print a summary of the model
summary(BPRS_rism)

We get a chi squared of 63.6 with 2 degrees of freedom, and a p of 1.499e-14 indicating that this model with random intercepts and slopes for different subjects is a better fit than the previous model with only random intercepts.

The model with an interaction of time and treatment is not significantly better than the previous one. (p = 0.18) Thus finally we plot the original plot with measured bprs and a plot with fitted values from the random slope + intercept model without interaction of time and treatment.

# draw the plot of BPRSL with the observed bprs scores
ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = bprs, group = subject2)) +
  geom_line(aes(colour = treatment)) +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Time (weeks)", breaks = seq(0, 8, 1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "BPRS score") +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

# Create a vector of the fitted values
Fitted <- fitted(BPRS_rism)
# Create a new column fitted to BPRSL

BPRSL <- mutate(BPRSL, FittedBPRS = Fitted)
# draw the plot of BPRSL with the Fitted values of bprs scores
ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = FittedBPRS, group = subject2)) +
  geom_line(aes(colour = treatment)) +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Time (weeks)", breaks = seq(0, 8, 1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Fitted BPRS score") +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

Graphically this is not as demonstrative of a good fit as with the RATS data in the book and datacamp excercises. However, I think a downwards trend in bprs scores can be seen clearlier in the fitted data than in the actual data.
